      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pale and tasteless dough is often a failure because the moisture content is too high or the heat is too low, preventing the Maillard reaction from reaching its necessary temperature threshold to activate. Conversely, a bitter, burnt taste occurs when the reaction progresses too far into the carbonization stage, breaking down the desirable compounds into acrid flavors. You can prevent these issues by ensuring a dry crust environment and carefully timing your oven temperature to strike a balance between browning and burning.",
